Communicate Data Findings:February 2019 Ford GoBike TourData Exploration¶

by Ajogi Paul Iye¶

Introduction¶

This project's dataset comprises 183412 cases of trips from place to place about the SanFrancisco Bay Area, inclusive of tour duration, start and end time of tours for February 2019

Data Assessing and Cleaning¶

1 .Drop null values in start_station_id,start_station_name,end_station_id,end_station_name,member_birth_year,member_gender¶

2 .Convert Datatype of member_birth_year from float to int¶

3 .Change start_time and end_time from object to datetime¶

4 .Change to categorical variable user_type,member_gender,bike_share_share_for_all_trip¶

5 .Create new column for day of the week and time of the day¶

6 .Convert Datatype of duration_sec from integer to minutes¶

7 .Convert member_birth_year to user year¶

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset contains 174952 observations with 18 features(member_gender,bike_share_for_all,user_type,duration_min,station_id, and many others).

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

. What time spent in making use of service is of utmost interest to me and the category of users that make use of the tours the most. This will enable the Fordgobike company to know the category that generates revenue the most and to tailor their services to involve a broader category of people

. I am most interested in finding out what destination the user of this services use the most

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

i. member_gender

ii. bike_share_for_all_trip

iii. user_type

iv. duration_min

v. end_station_id

What is the shape of duration_min?

Visualization¶

In [247]:
# code for plotting
def plot_hist(data,size,var,log_plot=False):
    if log_plot:
        plt.figure(figsize=[9,6]);
        bins=10**np.arange(np.log10(data['duration_min'].min()),np.log10(data['duration_min'].max())+size,size)
        plt.hist(data=data,x=var,bins=bins);
        plt.xscale('log');
        
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=[9,6]);
        bins=np.arange(data[var].min(),data[var].max()+size,size)
        plt.hist(data=data,x=var,bins=bins);
        
# plot graph
plot_hist(df_fordgobike,6,'duration_min',log_plot=False);
plt.xlim(0,200);

Discussion on the distribution(s) of variable(s) of interest.¶

I see duration_sec as a variable of interest to me as such to gain explicit insights here, duration_sec was converted to duration_min.When plotted at first, its spreading was right skewed ;this prompted my intiution which made me converted the scale and bins to log. The output shows that duration_min is truly unimodal with 100mins at its zenith

I extracted from the start_time variable AM or PM and save it in (time_of_day) as new variable;this was done to enable me explore the time_of_day that had more rendevous by users. Start_time was prefreably used as against end_time as it reliably showed the high percentage of spreading of users of bike in the afternoon and evening as compared to mornings

unusual distributions and operations performed on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data¶

A qualitative variable age was created from the user_age variable .This was done to give me a better insights about the relationships. Missing data was dropped from the dataset whoes result affected the columns-end_station_id,member_gender,member_birth_year.About 0.1% of the data came from 197 cases in the end_station_id variable while about 4.5% of the data came from member_gender and member_birth_year. However, after effective cleaning of the dataset, all variables now have 174952 instances while user_age replaced member_birth_year .

Observation¶

The boxplot depicts a medium of somewhat below 10min as regards all age category exception of the (80-100) group that has a wide distribution and very low median. Heatmap also shows a negative correlation between age and cycling times with the correlation of almost tending to zero. Furthermore, the scatter plot depicts a massive congestion of data points about age range from approximately (20 to 60) years as cycling time shots up to and above 8hrs(outliers evident here). This transcend to the fact that these age range cycle for longer hours as expected.

The company would generate lots of revenue from this age range(20 to 60) cycling activities as such all hands must be on deck so as to avoid downtime in their operations.

# examining for corr between duration_min,end_station_id,start_station_id
def plot_corr(data,var1,var2,):
    variables=[var1,var2,]
    fig, ax=plt.subplots(nrows=2,figsize=[7,7])
    
    for i in range(len(variables)):
        var=variables[i]
        ax[i].scatter(data=data,x=var,y='duration_min')
        ax[i].set_yscale('log')
        ax[i].set_xlabel(var);
        ax[i].set_ylabel('duration_min')
        
plot_corr(df_fordgobike,'end_station_id','start_station_id')

The relationships you observed in this part of the investigation.¶

The question posed to this dataset was answered based on the insights gathered from the analysis thus far. I observed a huge rendevous with the company services by users that spanned (20 to 40)years old over other age category. Based on the yardstick (numbers), subscriber type user had extra rendevous than customer type user although further examination showed that irrespective of smaller number of customer type user, they also had rendevous with regards to average cycling duration. Comparable trend was also evident in member_gender column as smaller amount of other gender had many mean cycling duration.This implies that on the average, the age range of (20 to 40)years old subscriber male had shorter cycling time but higher total cycling duration time. Thus the subscriber male often rendevous in shorter tours spending less amount of time with the company services

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

i. For "Other" gender group, there is high variance in the mornings and evenings as expected

ii. Male subscribers in the age category of (20 to 40)years that do not use the bike_share_for_all services generates more revenue than the others.

iii. The "Other" gender subscriber type that uses the bike_share_for_all services generates the least revenue for the company

Conclusions¶

. The age range of (20 to 40)years old are the category that ride bike the most while the old age(80 to 100) do not involve in this activity

. The "Male" gender makes the most of the Ford Gobike services followed by "Female" and the "Others"

. Thursdays have the highest peak of riders while weekends have the least riders

. Afternoons and evenings is the time of the day that has heavy traffic of riders which implies that most rendevous happens at this time of the day

. The age range of (20 to 60)years are heavily involved in the cycling activities. This goes a long way to let us know that the bike company generates a lot of revenue from this age category.

. Subscriber type are numerous in number while customer type are lesser number although on the average, the customer category have more cycling time.
